does what others rarely do: venture to the immigrants' home country and analyze racism there in relation to racial hierarchies in the United States. Attentive to history, the book considers the origins, nature, and extent of racial ideas about Koreans/Asians in relation to White and Black Americans, investigating how immigrants engage these ideas before they depart for the United States, as well as after they arrive. The author shows that contemporary globalization involves not just the flow of capital, but also culture. Ideas about American color lines and citizenship lines have crossed oceans alongside U.S. commodities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362713040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503627130423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503627130/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles